<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=98429796484692></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98429796484692><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj><a href=/strategy/classes.html?class=9&mid=98429796484692 style='color: darkblue;'>RE: best class for shaman</a></span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?id=2076><span id=Sage>Pusbag</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>529 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Mar 11th 3:06 AM</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.57]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>*Ahem*<br>/em Pusbag clears his throat and opens his maw to speak.<br><br>Let's not beat around the bush, shall we?  <br>I am not going denigrate the other races by pointing out their multitudinous and spectacular faults and weaknesses.  I am not going to say that I am not prejudiced and some of my best friends are Barbarians or such.  And I am not going to say that all classes or races are equal to and need each other to move forward in the game.<br><br>The simple fact and reason for this is that the Troll is king!  We need no other race or class to further our interests.  Come on.  Say it with me:  "The Troll is king."  Feels good rolling off your tongue, doesn't it?  The truth ALWAYS feels good.  As the Good Book says, "The shaman's diseases burn the soul as well as the strength of those who oppose him. (Pusbagicus I, chap 13, vs 3)" and "The Way of the Troll is long and arduous, but many are the rewards of those who persevere. (Pusbagicus IV, chap 27, vs 12). What?  Which Good Book were you thinking of?<br><br>We could argue long into the night over many a beer about the attributes of one race over another, but really, it comes down to this one issue:  roleplaying.  A Barbie or a Cleetus both lack that vital component in roleplaying that is essential to immersing yourself in that avatar you oh so carefully created-- believability.  <br>Believability is that core element that differenciates EverQuest from a first person shooter.  Indeed, many people I know treat EQ as a game much like a shooter in that the more monsters you kill the better the chances to "upgrade" their weapons, equipment, etc.  This is the thing that separates this kind of game from others.  At the risk of pointing out the obvious, EQ is an RPG, hence the roleplaying aspect of it.  If you wanted to shoot things why not play Tribes or something?<br><br>Now, I understand that you could roleplay a Barbie or a Cleetus if you wanted to.  All you have to do is talk in a brogue or act like a simpleton to get your point across.  Iksars are a bit harder in that you have to think like a lizard (I'm not sure that putting six or seven S's on the end of words constitutes roleplaying), but I suppose it could be done with some effort.  But why?!?  But the Troll is KING when it comes to roleplaying!  We are evil, conniving, cunning, vicious, cruel, and hungry.  Some people use a badly spelled form of english with their trolls that connotates a poor level of skill with the spoken language, but I prefer to use emotes and talk in Trollese.  This facilitates the inate obnoxious nature and poor socialization of the trollen race by annoying people who wish to go right back out there and level up with the SoW and buffs you have made them pay dearly for.<br><br>So, in closing, I recommend my chosen race-- the Troll.  How can you possibly go wrong?<br><br>--Pusbag Infection, who as far as you know, might BE the King of the Trolls.<br><br>/em Pusbag waves his royal scepter at the supplicant seeking answers and wisdom to humbly approach his throne.<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
